WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:09.000
Great Expectations by Charles Dickens, copyright, black cat publishing.

00:09.000 --> 00:27.000
Charles Dickens

00:27.000 --> 00:33.000
I am Charles Dickens. I am a famous writer.

00:33.000 --> 00:36.000
Do you know the names of some of my books?

00:36.000 --> 00:45.000
Oliver Twist, David Copperfield, A Tale of Two Cities, Great Expectations?

00:45.000 --> 00:48.000
Victoria is the Queen.

00:48.000 --> 00:53.000
England is a very important country in my time.

00:53.000 --> 01:00.000
It has a lot of power in the world, from Europe to India and China.

01:00.000 --> 01:04.000
But there are a lot of poor people in England.

01:04.000 --> 01:09.000
The rich ladies and gentlemen don't care about them.

01:09.000 --> 01:12.000
But I am sorry for the poor people.

01:12.000 --> 01:15.000
That is why I write my stories.

01:15.000 --> 01:20.000
I want to show that money is not important.

01:20.000 --> 01:25.000
In my story, Pip is a good boy when he is poor.

01:25.000 --> 01:31.000
But when he is a gentleman, he is cold and unkind.

01:31.000 --> 01:34.000
It isn't good to think about money.

01:34.000 --> 01:38.000
It is better to think about people.

01:38.000 --> 01:41.000
Read my story.

01:41.000 --> 01:47.000
Do you agree?

01:47.000 --> 01:53.000
Part 1, the prisoner on the marshes.

01:53.000 --> 01:58.000
Pip is a young boy. He has no mother and father.

01:58.000 --> 02:03.000
He lives on the marshes near the Great River Thames.

02:03.000 --> 02:07.000
One day, he is sitting in the churchyard.

02:07.000 --> 02:10.000
He is looking at his parents' graves.

02:10.000 --> 02:15.000
Suddenly, someone grabs him. It's a prisoner.

02:15.000 --> 02:19.000
He is escaping from the prison ships on the river.

02:19.000 --> 02:22.000
Pip is very afraid.

02:23.000 --> 02:25.000
What's your name?

02:25.000 --> 02:27.000
Pip, sir.

02:27.000 --> 02:30.000
I want food. Get me some.

02:30.000 --> 02:33.000
Yes, sir. You must be very hungry, sir.

02:33.000 --> 02:39.000
Yes, I am. And bring me a file to cut these chains.

02:39.000 --> 02:42.000
But don't tell anyone.

02:42.000 --> 02:44.000
No, sir.

02:44.000 --> 02:47.000
Pip runs back to the house.

02:47.000 --> 02:51.000
He lives with his sister and her husband, Joe.

02:51.000 --> 02:54.000
They are poor, simple people.

02:54.000 --> 02:58.000
Joe is the village blacksmith, and he is very kind.

02:58.000 --> 03:01.000
He loves Pip.

03:01.000 --> 03:05.000
But Pip's sister is nasty and bad-tempered.

03:05.000 --> 03:09.000
She likes hitting her little brother.

03:09.000 --> 03:16.000
In the middle of the night, Pip steals some food from the kitchen for the prisoner.

03:16.000 --> 03:19.000
You are a bad boy.

03:19.000 --> 03:22.000
Get me some food.

03:22.000 --> 03:27.000
I'm afraid of my sister, but I'm very afraid of the prisoner.

03:27.000 --> 03:31.000
It's very bad to steal food, but I must do it.

03:31.000 --> 03:37.000
Where is Joe's file? I must take it to help the prisoner.

03:37.000 --> 03:41.000
Pip gets up early and runs across the marshes.

03:41.000 --> 03:44.000
It is very cold and misty.

03:44.000 --> 03:47.000
The sun is rising.

03:47.000 --> 03:52.000
He sees another prisoner, but the man runs away.

03:52.000 --> 03:57.000
Pip takes the food and the file to the prisoner in the churchyard.

03:57.000 --> 04:02.000
Here is the food. You must be very cold and hungry, sir.

04:02.000 --> 04:06.000
Thank you, boy. This food is good.

04:06.000 --> 04:12.000
There's another prisoner on the marshes, sir. He has a scar on his face.

04:12.000 --> 04:16.000
What? He is my enemy. Give me the file.

04:16.000 --> 04:20.000
Quick! I must find him.

04:20.000 --> 04:23.000
Pip goes back to the house.

04:23.000 --> 04:29.000
When his sister cannot find the food for dinner, she is very angry.

04:29.000 --> 04:34.000
But then some soldiers arrive. They want Joe to help them.

04:34.000 --> 04:37.000
He must mend their equipment.

04:37.000 --> 04:40.000
The soldiers are looking for the prisoners.

04:40.000 --> 04:44.000
Joe takes Pip to the marshes to watch.

04:44.000 --> 04:50.000
The soldiers find the prisoners. They are fighting because they are enemies.

04:50.000 --> 04:54.000
The soldiers take the prisoners back to the prison ship.

04:54.000 --> 05:01.000
I'm afraid. The prisoner thinks that I'm helping the soldiers. It isn't true.

05:01.000 --> 05:05.000
The soldiers are taking the prisoners to the prison ship.

05:05.000 --> 05:08.000
Poor men, I'm sorry for them.

05:08.000 --> 05:13.000
You are my enemy. I want to kill you.

05:13.000 --> 05:19.000
You're stupid. Now we're both going back to prison.

05:23.000 --> 05:28.000
Part two, Miss Havisham.

05:28.000 --> 05:33.000
A strange old lady lives in a big house in the village.

05:33.000 --> 05:36.000
Her name is Miss Havisham.

05:36.000 --> 05:41.000
One day, she asks Pip's uncle to send Pip to her.

05:41.000 --> 05:46.000
She wants to see a child. His sister says...

05:46.000 --> 05:51.000
Miss Havisham is very rich. You must be polite, Pip.

05:51.000 --> 05:56.000
Perhaps she wants to give you a lot of money.

05:56.000 --> 06:03.000
Good luck, Pip. Be careful. Some people say Miss Havisham is mad.

06:03.000 --> 06:10.000
Uncle Pumblechuck takes Pip to her house. Its name is Satis House.

06:10.000 --> 06:18.000
A beautiful young girl opens the gate for Pip. She is very proud.

06:18.000 --> 06:25.000
Come in, boy. Miss Havisham wants to see you. But I don't like you.

06:25.000 --> 06:29.000
Your boots are dirty and your hands are rough.

06:29.000 --> 06:32.000
Is Miss Havisham your mother?

06:32.000 --> 06:38.000
No. I have no mother or father. But I live with Miss Havisham

06:38.000 --> 06:45.000
and she gives me everything. But don't ask questions, boy.

06:45.000 --> 06:52.000
Miss Havisham is sitting in a dark room. She is wearing an old wedding dress.

06:52.000 --> 06:58.000
It isn't white. It's yellow because it's very old.

06:58.000 --> 07:06.000
There are a lot of clocks, but they aren't working. They all say the same time.

07:06.000 --> 07:09.000
Twenty to nine.

07:09.000 --> 07:15.000
Hello, Pip. Well, Estella, do you like Pip?

07:15.000 --> 07:25.000
No. He isn't a gentleman. He's a blacksmith's boy. And Pip, do you like Estella?

07:25.000 --> 07:28.000
She's very beautiful.

07:28.000 --> 07:35.000
Pip thinks you're beautiful, Estella. So break his heart.

07:36.000 --> 07:41.000
Pip visits Miss Havisham and Estella many times.

07:41.000 --> 07:46.000
Sometimes they play cards. Sometimes they sing.

07:46.000 --> 07:50.000
But Estella is always proud.

07:50.000 --> 07:56.000
Pip begins to love her, but she doesn't love him.

07:56.000 --> 08:01.000
One day Miss Havisham takes him into a special room.

08:01.000 --> 08:07.000
There is a long table with a very old wedding cake on it.

08:07.000 --> 08:13.000
Spiders and mice and rats are everywhere.

08:13.000 --> 08:20.000
Today is my birthday, Pip. Push me around the table.

08:20.000 --> 08:25.000
This is my wedding cake from a long time ago.

08:25.000 --> 08:28.000
But where is her husband?

08:28.000 --> 08:35.000
I hate men. I am teaching Estella to hate men too, Pip.

08:35.000 --> 08:43.000
You are only a boy. But when you are a man, you must leave Satis House forever.

08:43.000 --> 08:46.000
But I want to marry Estella.

08:46.000 --> 08:51.000
Silly boy, I hate you.

08:51.000 --> 08:57.000
One day, Pip meets another boy in the garden. They fight.

08:57.000 --> 09:04.000
The boy boxes like a gentleman, but Pip wins because he fights like a blacksmith.

09:04.000 --> 09:09.000
Estella is watching the fight.

09:09.000 --> 09:12.000
You're the winner.

09:12.000 --> 09:17.000
Well done, Pip. You may kiss me if you like.

09:17.000 --> 09:25.000
Pip kisses Estella on the cheek. Later, Miss Havisham says goodbye to him.

09:25.000 --> 09:32.000
This is the last time, Pip. I don't want to see you again.

09:32.000 --> 09:38.000
Here is some money. You must be a blacksmith.

09:38.000 --> 09:42.000
But I want to see Estella again. I love her.

09:42.000 --> 09:49.000
I am sending Estella to Paris. I am making her a lady.

09:49.000 --> 10:01.000
But you are a blacksmith, Pip. You must work with Joe Godgeri.

10:01.000 --> 10:09.000
Great expectations and Kent. Rochester.

10:09.000 --> 10:16.000
Rochester is a historic city in Kent, near London.

10:16.000 --> 10:22.000
It has a very old cathedral and a Norman castle.

10:22.000 --> 10:28.000
The castle is almost a thousand years old.

10:28.000 --> 10:32.000
Dickens was in Rochester a lot.

10:32.000 --> 10:38.000
His house, Gad's Hill Place, is near Rochester.

10:38.000 --> 10:49.000
There is a Dickens Museum in Rochester and a Dickens Festival every summer and every Christmas.

10:49.000 --> 10:55.000
Great expectations takes place in Kent and London.

10:55.000 --> 10:59.000
Joe's Forge is near Rochester.

10:59.000 --> 11:04.000
The coach to London goes from Rochester.

11:04.000 --> 11:10.000
There is a house in Rochester called Restoration House.

11:10.000 --> 11:20.000
Dickens describes this house when he tells us about Satis House, where Miss Havisham lives.

11:20.000 --> 11:26.000
Near Rochester, on the marshes, there is the village of Kooling.

11:26.000 --> 11:31.000
It has a churchyard with a lot of graves.

11:32.000 --> 11:39.000
At the beginning of the story, Pip meets the prisoner in this churchyard.

11:39.000 --> 11:47.000
The churchyard is near Gad's Hill Place, but Dickens is not here.

11:47.000 --> 11:55.000
His body is in Westminster Abbey in London, in Poet's Corner.

11:55.000 --> 12:02.000
This is a special part of the Abbey for famous writers.

12:02.000 --> 12:07.000
There is another village called Chalk.

12:07.000 --> 12:10.000
Here you can see a forge.

12:10.000 --> 12:15.000
Dickens was in Chalk for his honeymoon.

12:15.000 --> 12:20.000
Perhaps this is Joe's Forge.

12:21.000 --> 12:26.000
Blacksmiths are very important in Victorian times.

12:26.000 --> 12:31.000
Horses are the main method of transport.

12:31.000 --> 12:35.000
Everyone needs horseshoes.

12:35.000 --> 12:41.000
People also need metal for other things.

12:41.000 --> 12:45.000
Do you know what is the most common English surname?

12:45.000 --> 12:48.000
It's Smith.

12:48.000 --> 12:52.000
Someone who works with metal.

12:52.000 --> 12:59.000
Joe Gargery is poor, but he is very important.

12:59.000 --> 13:07.000
If you visit Rochester, you can also see Uncle Pumblechook's shop in the High Street.

13:07.000 --> 13:13.000
You can see the inn, where there were the coaches for London.

13:13.000 --> 13:17.000
The mouth of the Thames is near Rochester.

13:17.000 --> 13:26.000
There is a great area of marshes, but the prison ships are not here now.

13:26.000 --> 13:29.000
There are no blacksmiths.

13:29.000 --> 13:34.000
People don't travel to London by coach and horses.

13:34.000 --> 13:40.000
Everything is very different in the 21st century.

13:44.000 --> 13:47.000
Part 3.

13:47.000 --> 13:50.000
The Money

13:50.000 --> 13:53.000
Pip works with Joe.

13:53.000 --> 13:57.000
He loves Joe and Joe loves him.

13:57.000 --> 14:02.000
But Pip is unhappy because he isn't a gentleman.

14:02.000 --> 14:06.000
He is 18 years old now.

14:06.000 --> 14:12.000
When Pip's sister is ill, a young woman comes to help Joe.

14:12.000 --> 14:15.000
Her name is Biddy.

14:15.000 --> 14:20.000
She is kind, generous and very pretty.

14:20.000 --> 14:27.000
She likes Pip very much, but Pip cannot forget Estella.

14:27.000 --> 14:29.000
I want to be a gentleman, Biddy.

14:29.000 --> 14:31.000
I want to marry Estella.

14:31.000 --> 14:34.000
I want to live in London.

14:34.000 --> 14:38.000
I am happy here with you and Joe, Pip.

14:38.000 --> 14:43.000
Joe isn't a gentleman, but he's a very good man.

14:43.000 --> 14:46.000
Yes, you're right.

14:46.000 --> 14:49.000
The marsh is beautiful.

14:49.000 --> 14:57.000
I'm not a lady and I'm not rich, but I like my life.

14:57.000 --> 15:01.000
One day, a visitor comes to the forge.

15:01.000 --> 15:04.000
His name is Mr. Jaggers.

15:04.000 --> 15:08.000
He is a lawyer from London.

15:08.000 --> 15:10.000
Is your name Pip?

15:10.000 --> 15:12.000
Yes, sir.

15:12.000 --> 15:14.000
I have news for you.

15:14.000 --> 15:16.000
You are rich.

15:16.000 --> 15:19.000
You have great expectations.

15:19.000 --> 15:23.000
What? I don't understand.

15:23.000 --> 15:27.000
Someone wants to give you a lot of money.

15:27.000 --> 15:29.000
You must go to London.

15:29.000 --> 15:33.000
You must learn to be a gentleman.

15:34.000 --> 15:37.000
It is a big surprise for Pip.

15:37.000 --> 15:41.000
Joe and Biddy are very sad.

15:41.000 --> 15:44.000
They don't want to lose Pip.

15:44.000 --> 15:46.000
Who is my benefactor, sir?

15:46.000 --> 15:51.000
It's a secret. I must not tell you the name.

15:51.000 --> 15:53.000
Is it a man or a woman?

15:53.000 --> 15:56.000
I must not tell you.

15:56.000 --> 15:59.000
Don't ask any more questions.

15:59.000 --> 16:01.000
Take this money.

16:01.000 --> 16:04.000
Buy some gentlemen's clothes.

16:04.000 --> 16:07.000
Miss Havisham must be the person.

16:07.000 --> 16:09.000
She wants me to be a gentleman.

16:09.000 --> 16:12.000
She wants Estella to be a lady.

16:12.000 --> 16:14.000
She wants us to marry.

16:14.000 --> 16:17.000
I am very happy.

16:17.000 --> 16:20.000
Pip leaves the village.

16:20.000 --> 16:23.000
Joe and Biddy are crying.

16:23.000 --> 16:25.000
But Pip is happy.

16:25.000 --> 16:28.000
He is in the coach.

16:28.000 --> 16:31.000
He is thinking about the future.

16:36.000 --> 16:39.000
Goodbye, Pip. Remember us?

16:39.000 --> 16:42.000
Good luck in London, Pip.

16:42.000 --> 16:45.000
Don't forget us when you're a fine gentleman.

16:45.000 --> 16:47.000
I'm going to London.

16:47.000 --> 16:49.000
I can't believe it.

16:49.000 --> 16:55.000
I want to see St Paul's Cathedral and Westminster Abbey and the Queen's Palace.

16:55.000 --> 16:58.000
I have money. I have new clothes.

16:58.000 --> 17:01.000
I am a gentleman.

17:04.000 --> 17:09.000
Part 4. London.

17:09.000 --> 17:12.000
Pip arrives in London.

17:12.000 --> 17:16.000
He sees a big city for the first time.

17:16.000 --> 17:19.000
He forgets Joe and Biddy.

17:19.000 --> 17:23.000
He only thinks about Estella.

17:24.000 --> 17:28.000
He lives in Barnard's Inn in London.

17:28.000 --> 17:32.000
In his rooms, he meets Herbert Pocket.

17:32.000 --> 17:35.000
Hello. My name's Herbert.

17:35.000 --> 17:39.000
Hello. I'm Pip. I remember you.

17:39.000 --> 17:42.000
You're the boy in Miss Havisham's garden.

17:42.000 --> 17:45.000
Yes. But now we are friends.

17:45.000 --> 17:47.000
I want to show you London.

17:47.000 --> 17:49.000
My father is a teacher.

17:49.000 --> 17:51.000
He can help you to be a gentleman.

17:51.000 --> 17:55.000
Then I can marry Estella.

17:55.000 --> 18:00.000
Herbert is telling Pip about Miss Havisham. He says,

18:00.000 --> 18:05.000
Be careful, Pip. Miss Havisham hates men.

18:05.000 --> 18:12.000
Many years ago, she was in love, but on her wedding day, the man wasn't at the church.

18:12.000 --> 18:19.000
The time was 20 to 9. Estella hates men too.

18:19.000 --> 18:26.000
I cannot marry you. I love your money, but I don't love you.

18:26.000 --> 18:32.000
Ah! This is terrible. Stop the clocks.

18:32.000 --> 18:38.000
Close the curtains. I don't want to live in the world.

18:38.000 --> 18:44.000
Pip learns to be a gentleman. He learns to eat politely.

18:44.000 --> 18:47.000
He learns to speak politely.

18:47.000 --> 18:51.000
He learns to behave politely.

18:51.000 --> 18:56.000
Joe visits him in London, but he doesn't stay long.

18:56.000 --> 19:01.000
Pip doesn't want to talk to his old friend, the blacksmith.

19:01.000 --> 19:04.000
Pip is a snob.

19:04.000 --> 19:10.000
You're a fine gentleman now, Pip. You have fine clothes.

19:10.000 --> 19:14.000
Thank you, Joe. Biddy sends you her best wishes, Pip.

19:14.000 --> 19:19.000
Thank you, Joe. I'm going back to the village now, Pip.

19:19.000 --> 19:25.000
I don't belong in London. Goodbye, Joe.

19:25.000 --> 19:30.000
Joe is unhappy. He loves Pip.

19:30.000 --> 19:34.000
Pip buys new clothes and new furniture.

19:34.000 --> 19:39.000
Mr. Jaggers always has money to give him.

19:39.000 --> 19:44.000
Mr. Wemmick, my clerk, has some money for you, Pip.

19:44.000 --> 19:46.000
How much do you want?

19:46.000 --> 19:49.000
A lot, Mr. Jaggers.

19:49.000 --> 19:54.000
All right, Pip. You are 21 years old this year.

19:54.000 --> 19:58.000
Your benefactor wants to give you more money.

19:58.000 --> 20:02.000
But who is my benefactor? It's Miss Havisham, isn't it?

20:02.000 --> 20:04.000
I cannot tell you.

20:04.000 --> 20:07.000
Here is your money, sir.

20:07.000 --> 20:19.000
Pip is very happy. He is a rich gentleman. He can marry Estella.

20:19.000 --> 20:22.000
Orphans.

20:22.000 --> 20:27.000
An orphan is a child without parents.

20:27.000 --> 20:33.000
There are two important orphans in the story of great expectations.

20:33.000 --> 20:37.000
Pip and Estella.

20:37.000 --> 20:42.000
Pip lives with his sister and Joe Godgeri.

20:42.000 --> 20:46.000
Estella lives with Miss Havisham.

20:46.000 --> 20:50.000
Who has the better life?

20:50.000 --> 20:56.000
Pip, with his life on the marshes and Joe who loves him,

20:56.000 --> 21:02.000
or Estella with Miss Havisham's jewels and money.

21:02.000 --> 21:08.000
In the story, Pip looks for substitute fathers.

21:08.000 --> 21:14.000
As you read the story, think about this idea.

21:14.000 --> 21:18.000
Who takes the place of Pip's dead father?

21:18.000 --> 21:24.000
Who takes the place of Pip's dead mother?

21:24.000 --> 21:30.000
It is very hard to be an orphan in the 19th century.

21:30.000 --> 21:36.000
If you are rich, maybe there are rich relations who look after you.

21:36.000 --> 21:42.000
But if you are poor, no one helps you.

21:42.000 --> 21:47.000
There are a lot of orphans in the stories of Dickens.

21:47.000 --> 21:52.000
Oliver Twist is the most famous one.

21:52.000 --> 21:55.000
He must live in the workhouse.

21:55.000 --> 22:02.000
That is a place for poor people who have no money and no job.

22:02.000 --> 22:08.000
The local government gives them a place to live and food.

22:08.000 --> 22:12.000
But they must work and follow the rules.

22:12.000 --> 22:18.000
The food is bad and the work is hard.

22:18.000 --> 22:26.000
People in the times of Dickens are afraid of the workhouse.

22:26.000 --> 22:33.000
Some orphans live in special places called orphanages.

22:33.000 --> 22:39.000
Some of these orphanages are very bad.

22:39.000 --> 22:45.000
Dickens writes about another orphan in his book, David Copperfield.

22:45.000 --> 22:55.000
And another writer, Charlotte Bronte, writes about Jane Eyre, a girl orphan.

22:55.000 --> 23:01.000
Why are there a lot of orphans in Victorian times?

23:01.000 --> 23:07.000
Sometimes life is dangerous, especially for poor people.

23:07.000 --> 23:14.000
It is easy to die in an accident, in a factory or on a farm.

23:14.000 --> 23:19.000
Doctors and hospitals are not very advanced.

23:19.000 --> 23:23.000
Parents often die young from diseases.

23:23.000 --> 23:27.000
It is dangerous for women to have children.

23:27.000 --> 23:31.000
Women often die in childbirth.

23:31.000 --> 23:33.000
We are lucky.

23:33.000 --> 23:39.000
We live in the 21st century, and health care is much better.

23:39.000 --> 23:44.000
We understand diseases better and how to avoid them.

23:44.000 --> 23:54.000
People do not live as long in Victorian times.

23:54.000 --> 23:59.000
Part 5, Estella in London.

23:59.000 --> 24:03.000
Estella comes back from Paris.

24:03.000 --> 24:09.000
Now she is a lady, and Pip is a gentleman.

24:09.000 --> 24:16.000
Pip goes to visit Miss Havisham at Satis House and meets Estella.

24:16.000 --> 24:22.000
Pip thinks that Miss Havisham is his benefactor.

24:22.000 --> 24:29.000
You are rich now, Pip, but the name of your benefactor is secret, I think.

24:29.000 --> 24:33.000
Yes, Miss Havisham, but I am very grateful.

24:33.000 --> 24:39.000
Good. Look, here is Estella.

24:39.000 --> 24:43.000
You are very beautiful, Estella.

24:43.000 --> 24:47.000
Ah, it is the blacksmith's boy.

24:47.000 --> 24:53.000
You are a gentleman now. Your shoes are clean.

24:53.000 --> 24:56.000
Miss Havisham is happy.

24:56.000 --> 25:00.000
She wants Estella to break the hearts of men.

25:00.000 --> 25:05.000
This is Miss Havisham's revenge.

25:05.000 --> 25:07.000
Is she beautiful?

25:07.000 --> 25:08.000
She asks Pip.

25:08.000 --> 25:11.000
Yes, he says.

25:11.000 --> 25:13.000
Love her, Pip.

25:13.000 --> 25:15.000
Says Miss Havisham.

25:15.000 --> 25:21.000
Love her, love her, love her.

25:21.000 --> 25:24.000
Estella comes to London.

25:24.000 --> 25:30.000
Pip is her friend, but she flirts with a lot of men.

25:30.000 --> 25:32.000
Pip is jealous.

25:32.000 --> 25:37.000
At a party, he is talking to Estella.

25:37.000 --> 25:41.000
Estella, don't dance with other men.

25:41.000 --> 25:43.000
Don't smile at them.

25:43.000 --> 25:44.000
Marry me.

25:44.000 --> 25:46.000
I am a gentleman now.

25:46.000 --> 25:48.000
I love you.

25:48.000 --> 25:50.000
Don't be silly, Pip.

25:50.000 --> 25:52.000
I have no heart.

25:52.000 --> 25:57.000
I cannot love you. I can only make you unhappy.

25:57.000 --> 26:00.000
Do you want to dance, Miss Estella?

26:00.000 --> 26:03.000
Yes, thank you, sir.

26:03.000 --> 26:04.000
Goodbye, Pip.

26:10.000 --> 26:13.000
Pip is very sad.

26:13.000 --> 26:16.000
Herbert wants to help his friend.

26:16.000 --> 26:19.000
He tells him to forget Estella.

26:19.000 --> 26:23.000
But I love her, says Pip.

26:23.000 --> 26:28.000
Pip is drinking with Herbert and some other students.

26:28.000 --> 26:32.000
Every man drinks to a lady.

26:32.000 --> 26:35.000
Bentley Drummel is there.

26:35.000 --> 26:41.000
He is rich and handsome, but he has a bad reputation.

26:41.000 --> 26:43.000
He raises his glass.

26:44.000 --> 26:50.000
To Estella, the most beautiful woman in London.

26:50.000 --> 26:52.000
Pip is angry.

26:52.000 --> 26:57.000
You cannot drink to Estella. You don't know her.

26:57.000 --> 27:01.000
Why not? I know her well.

27:01.000 --> 27:06.000
She is my special friend. I often dance with her.

27:06.000 --> 27:09.000
You are lying.

27:09.000 --> 27:12.000
Herbert tells Pip to be careful.

27:12.000 --> 27:15.000
Everyone is listening.

27:15.000 --> 27:21.000
Later, Bentley Drummel shows everybody a letter from Estella.

27:21.000 --> 27:24.000
She writes...

27:24.000 --> 27:27.000
Yes, I know Mr Drummel.

27:27.000 --> 27:31.000
Sometimes I dance with him. Estella.

27:31.000 --> 27:34.000
Pip must apologize.

27:34.000 --> 27:37.000
I am sorry, he says.

27:37.000 --> 27:41.000
You are right. You are not a liar.

27:41.000 --> 27:45.000
And you, sir, are not a gentleman.

27:45.000 --> 27:48.000
The other students laugh at Pip.

27:54.000 --> 27:57.000
Pip goes to see Estella.

27:57.000 --> 28:01.000
Estella, why do you see Bentley Drummel?

28:01.000 --> 28:04.000
Estella answers...

28:04.000 --> 28:07.000
There are lots of men in my life, Pip.

28:07.000 --> 28:10.000
I am very beautiful.

28:10.000 --> 28:13.000
Miss Havisham gives me a lot of money.

28:13.000 --> 28:16.000
They all want to marry me.

28:16.000 --> 28:20.000
But Estella, Drummel is a horrible person.

28:20.000 --> 28:24.000
He is cruel and stupid.

28:24.000 --> 28:29.000
I like cruel, stupid, rich men.

28:29.000 --> 28:33.000
Remember, Pip, I have no heart.

28:33.000 --> 28:36.000
Biddy writes to Pip.

28:36.000 --> 28:41.000
Pip's sister, Joe's wife, is dead.

28:41.000 --> 28:44.000
Pip goes back to the village.

28:44.000 --> 28:49.000
After the funeral, he speaks to Biddy.

28:49.000 --> 28:52.000
Joe is very sad, Pip.

28:52.000 --> 28:55.000
You never write to him or visit us.

28:55.000 --> 28:57.000
I am sorry, Biddy.

28:57.000 --> 29:01.000
But don't worry. I want to visit Joe often now.

29:01.000 --> 29:05.000
My sister is dead, and he is alone.

29:05.000 --> 29:07.000
I don't believe you, Pip.

29:07.000 --> 29:12.000
You're a gentleman now, and you don't want to remember Joe and me.

29:12.000 --> 29:16.000
No, Biddy. I miss you.

29:16.000 --> 29:20.000
But Pip doesn't visit them.

29:20.000 --> 29:25.000
He always thinks about Estella and Miss Havisham.

29:25.000 --> 29:28.000
He forgets his real friends.

29:32.000 --> 29:37.000
Part six, the visitor.

29:37.000 --> 29:41.000
One night, Pip is studying at home.

29:41.000 --> 29:44.000
It is a dark stormy night.

29:44.000 --> 29:49.000
He can hear the wind and the rain in the London streets.

29:49.000 --> 29:54.000
Suddenly, somebody knocks at the door.

29:54.000 --> 30:00.000
It is an old, rough-looking man.

30:01.000 --> 30:03.000
He is not a gentleman.

30:03.000 --> 30:06.000
Who are you? What do you want?

30:06.000 --> 30:10.000
My boy. My boy.

30:10.000 --> 30:12.000
Do you recognize me?

30:12.000 --> 30:17.000
No. I don't know you. Please go away.

30:17.000 --> 30:22.000
But I know you. You are my gentleman.

30:22.000 --> 30:24.000
This is a mistake.

30:24.000 --> 30:27.000
No, there's no mistake.

30:28.000 --> 30:32.000
You are a gentleman because you have my money.

30:32.000 --> 30:35.000
You are my gentleman.

30:35.000 --> 30:39.000
Pip and the prisoner are talking.

30:39.000 --> 30:42.000
Do you remember the marshes?

30:42.000 --> 30:45.000
Do you remember the churchyard?

30:45.000 --> 30:47.000
Do you remember the prisoner?

30:47.000 --> 30:50.000
I am the prisoner.

30:50.000 --> 30:54.000
My name is Abel Magwitch.

30:54.000 --> 30:56.000
But this is impossible.

30:56.000 --> 31:00.000
No, dear boy. You helped me.

31:00.000 --> 31:02.000
I remember the food.

31:02.000 --> 31:05.000
I was a prisoner in Australia.

31:05.000 --> 31:08.000
Now I have a lot of money.

31:08.000 --> 31:11.000
I have a sheep farm in Australia.

31:11.000 --> 31:14.000
Jagger's is my lawyer.

31:14.000 --> 31:19.000
He gives you money from me, dear boy.

31:19.000 --> 31:22.000
I am in England to see you.

31:22.000 --> 31:25.000
Pip is very upset.

31:25.000 --> 31:30.000
I don't understand. Miss Havisham is my benefactor.

31:30.000 --> 31:32.000
Magwitch answers.

31:32.000 --> 31:35.000
No, no. You are wrong.

31:35.000 --> 31:44.000
This is terrible. I cannot take your money. I cannot marry Estella. I hate you.

31:44.000 --> 31:52.000
Now Pip knows the truth. He tells everything to his friends.

31:52.000 --> 31:58.000
It is dangerous for Abel, Pip. The police want to hang him. We must help him.

31:58.000 --> 32:02.000
Magwitch must return to Australia.

32:02.000 --> 32:07.000
It is the end of my dreams. I am poor again.

32:07.000 --> 32:13.000
Abel Magwitch must hide from the police. His enemy is looking for him.

32:13.000 --> 32:21.000
I am happy with you, Pip. You are like my son. I love you.

32:21.000 --> 32:25.000
I don't want to go back to Australia.

32:25.000 --> 32:31.000
Pip decides to help Magwitch. They must go to Australia together.

32:31.000 --> 32:36.000
First, he wants to see Joe and Biddy again.

32:36.000 --> 32:41.000
He goes back to the forge in the country.

32:41.000 --> 32:46.000
Pip, I am so glad to see you. How are you?

32:46.000 --> 32:51.000
I am sorry we have no good food or fine wine for a gentleman like you.

32:51.000 --> 32:55.000
Don't say that, Joe. I am not a gentleman now.

32:55.000 --> 33:01.000
It is a long story and I cannot tell you everything. It is a secret.

33:01.000 --> 33:04.000
But I am here to say goodbye.

33:04.000 --> 33:07.000
Goodbye? Where are you going?

33:07.000 --> 33:11.000
I am going to Australia. I cannot tell you anymore.

33:11.000 --> 33:14.000
But thank you, Joe and Biddy for everything.

33:14.000 --> 33:18.000
You are my best friends.

33:22.000 --> 33:26.000
Ladies and gentlemen.

33:26.000 --> 33:30.000
The 18th century.

33:30.000 --> 33:36.000
In the 18th century, everyone has a place in society.

33:36.000 --> 33:40.000
It is almost impossible to change.

33:40.000 --> 33:47.000
If a man belongs to a rich, important family, he is a gentleman.

33:47.000 --> 33:55.000
If a man belongs to a poor, unimportant family, he is an ordinary person

33:55.000 --> 33:59.000
and he can never be a gentleman.

33:59.000 --> 34:03.000
It is the same for women.

34:03.000 --> 34:08.000
The 19th century.

34:08.000 --> 34:13.000
In the time of Queen Victoria, it is different.

34:13.000 --> 34:21.000
Even a poor person can become a gentleman or a lady by working hard and becoming rich.

34:21.000 --> 34:26.000
It is not easy, but it is possible.

34:26.000 --> 34:33.000
It is the first time in history that people can change their place in society.

34:33.000 --> 34:37.000
Dickens himself is a good example.

34:37.000 --> 34:40.000
He comes from a poor family.

34:40.000 --> 34:44.000
His father is sometimes in prison.

34:44.000 --> 34:51.000
Dickens must work in a factory when he is a child to help his family.

34:51.000 --> 34:56.000
But Dickens begins to write and becomes popular.

34:56.000 --> 34:59.000
He makes a lot of money.

34:59.000 --> 35:03.000
He is intelligent and educated.

35:03.000 --> 35:07.000
He is a gentleman.

35:07.000 --> 35:13.000
In the story, Pip is also poor, but becomes a gentleman.

35:13.000 --> 35:18.000
First, he uses his benefact as money.

35:18.000 --> 35:28.000
But at the end of the story, he works hard for eleven years in the east and has his own money.

35:28.000 --> 35:32.000
What is a gentleman?

35:32.000 --> 35:36.000
In the story, Drummel is a gentleman.

35:36.000 --> 35:45.000
He belongs to a rich, important family, but he is cruel and stupid.

35:45.000 --> 35:50.000
When Pip is a boy, he is not a gentleman.

35:50.000 --> 35:56.000
Estella says that he has dirty boots and rough hands.

35:56.000 --> 36:02.000
Pip is a gentleman after he learns how to behave well.

36:02.000 --> 36:07.000
But where does his money come from?

36:07.000 --> 36:11.000
Joe is not a gentleman.

36:11.000 --> 36:14.000
He is poor and must work hard.

36:14.000 --> 36:21.000
He cannot read and write, but he is very kind and good.

36:21.000 --> 36:25.000
Who is the real gentleman?

36:25.000 --> 36:29.000
What do you think?

36:29.000 --> 36:33.000
What is a lady?

36:33.000 --> 36:38.000
Miss Havisham belongs to a rich, important family.

36:38.000 --> 36:49.000
Her money comes from her father, but she lives in a big house without daylight or time.

36:49.000 --> 36:53.000
Estella learns to be a lady in Paris.

36:53.000 --> 37:00.000
She has money and jewels, but she has no heart.

37:00.000 --> 37:10.000
Biddy is poor and must work hard, but she is kind and helps other people.

37:10.000 --> 37:15.000
Who is the real lady?

37:15.000 --> 37:20.000
Marriage is very important for Victorian ladies.

37:20.000 --> 37:29.000
If a man promises to marry a woman and then breaks his promise, the law punishes him.

37:29.000 --> 37:33.000
Be careful, boys.

37:33.000 --> 37:40.000
It is a terrible thing for Miss Havisham when her fiancé doesn't marry her.

37:40.000 --> 37:49.000
She almost goes crazy.

37:49.000 --> 37:54.000
Part 7. Fire.

37:54.000 --> 37:58.000
Pip wants to see Miss Havisham again.

37:58.000 --> 38:01.000
He visits Satis House.

38:01.000 --> 38:04.000
Estella is with Miss Havisham.

38:04.000 --> 38:08.000
Pip, why are you here?

38:08.000 --> 38:14.000
I know everything. You are not my benefactor. You don't care about me.

38:14.000 --> 38:17.000
I'm sorry, Pip.

38:17.000 --> 38:22.000
Estella, marry me. I'm poor again, but I love you.

38:22.000 --> 38:29.000
No, Pip. I cannot marry you. I want to marry Bentley Dremel.

38:29.000 --> 38:33.000
Pip and Miss Havisham are shocked.

38:33.000 --> 38:39.000
Pip, I know nothing about this. I cannot believe it.

38:39.000 --> 38:44.000
It is true, Miss Havisham. I want to be Mrs. Bentley Dremel.

38:44.000 --> 38:53.000
Forget me, Pip. Ungrateful girl. You have my money and my jewels and my love.

38:53.000 --> 39:02.000
I don't want you to marry a man. I hate all men. I want you here with me.

39:02.000 --> 39:05.000
Do you love me, Estella?

39:05.000 --> 39:11.000
No, Miss Havisham. I cannot love. I have no heart.

39:11.000 --> 39:14.000
That is your lesson to me.

39:14.000 --> 39:16.000
Goodbye, Pip.

39:16.000 --> 39:22.000
This is your fault, Miss Havisham. You are a bitter old woman.

39:22.000 --> 39:27.000
Estella has no heart because you taught her to hate men.

39:27.000 --> 39:33.000
She doesn't love Dremel. He is rich and handsome, but he is cruel.

39:33.000 --> 39:40.000
It is a terrible marriage. You are responsible. Goodbye.

39:41.000 --> 39:45.000
Pip leaves Satis House.

39:45.000 --> 39:52.000
Pip returns to London. There, someone gives Pip a letter from Wemmick.

39:52.000 --> 39:56.000
It says, don't go home.

39:56.000 --> 39:59.000
Pip visits Wemmick.

39:59.000 --> 40:04.000
Madwich has a lot of enemies. They know he is in London.

40:04.000 --> 40:10.000
They are following you because they want to find him. Abel must hide from them.

40:11.000 --> 40:17.000
Abel must stay with my friend, Clara, and her father. They live near the river.

40:17.000 --> 40:24.000
Pip agrees, but Miss Havisham asks him to visit her again.

40:24.000 --> 40:29.000
He goes back to Satis House. She says...

40:29.000 --> 40:37.000
You are sad. Estella is married to a terrible man. It is my fault.

40:37.000 --> 40:39.000
Do you forgive me?

40:39.000 --> 40:42.000
Yes. I forgive you.

40:42.000 --> 40:43.000
Says Pip.

40:43.000 --> 40:50.000
I want to help you, Pip. I want to give you money. I have a human heart.

40:50.000 --> 40:57.000
Thank you. But nobody can help me. I want Estella.

40:57.000 --> 41:01.000
Miss Havisham is sitting near the fire.

41:01.000 --> 41:06.000
Suddenly, her old wedding dress touches the fire.

41:06.000 --> 41:09.000
It begins to burn.

41:09.000 --> 41:18.000
Pip saves her, but the old clothes burn quickly. She is badly injured.

41:18.000 --> 41:23.000
Poor Miss Havisham. She has nothing now.

41:23.000 --> 41:28.000
He waits for the doctor. Then he thinks...

41:28.000 --> 41:34.000
I would like to see Joe and Biddy. They really love me.

41:34.000 --> 41:41.000
But I have no time. I must go back to London. I must save Abel Magwitch.

41:41.000 --> 41:44.000
His enemies want to catch him.

41:49.000 --> 41:54.000
Part 8. The Escape.

41:54.000 --> 42:01.000
Wemmick is helping Pip and Herbert. Magwitch must go back to Australia.

42:01.000 --> 42:04.000
They make a plan.

42:04.000 --> 42:10.000
There is a ship to Hamburg. You can meet it at the end of the River Thames.

42:10.000 --> 42:14.000
But no one must see you when you leave London.

42:14.000 --> 42:17.000
What can we do?

42:17.000 --> 42:26.000
Row on the river every day. Do the same thing every day. But one day, take Magwitch with you.

42:26.000 --> 42:31.000
Row to the end of the Thames, where it meets the sea.

42:31.000 --> 42:37.000
Catch the ship to Hamburg. Then go to Australia.

42:37.000 --> 42:40.000
Then Magwitch is safe.

42:40.000 --> 42:44.000
That's a great idea. Let's do it.

42:44.000 --> 42:50.000
One night, Pip and Herbert take their boat to meet Magwitch.

42:50.000 --> 42:53.000
He is wearing a disguise.

42:53.000 --> 43:02.000
They row towards the sea at the end of the Great River Thames.

43:02.000 --> 43:09.000
Thank you, Pip, my boy. But I don't want to be alone in Australia.

43:09.000 --> 43:17.000
Don't worry, Abel. I'm coming with you. There is nothing in England for me. Estella is married.

43:17.000 --> 43:26.000
I am very happy, Pip. You are my son. I want you to be with me.

43:26.000 --> 43:32.000
Shh. I think that someone is following us. We must be careful.

43:32.000 --> 43:37.000
The police mustn't catch Magwitch in England.

43:37.000 --> 43:42.000
They continue to go down the river.

43:42.000 --> 43:50.000
They hide on an island during the night. In the morning, they are looking for the big ship.

43:50.000 --> 43:59.000
Pip and Magwitch are going to Europe and then to Australia. They are escaping.

43:59.000 --> 44:10.000
They see the ship. But there is another boat. There are three policemen in it and another man.

44:10.000 --> 44:17.000
Look. There's the ship. Row quickly. We must catch it.

44:17.000 --> 44:20.000
That's Magwitch. Abel Magwitch.

44:20.000 --> 44:27.000
Stop. That man is a prisoner from Australia. You mustn't help him. Stop.

44:27.000 --> 44:32.000
Row faster. Faster. We must catch the ship.

44:32.000 --> 44:36.000
Who is that man in the boat with the police?

44:36.000 --> 44:42.000
I think that I can recognize him. It's my enemy, Comppison.

44:42.000 --> 44:51.000
Yes. The man in the other boat is Comppison. He is the other prisoner from the marshes.

44:51.000 --> 44:59.000
He is helping the police because he hates Magwitch. And Magwitch hates him.

45:00.000 --> 45:07.000
Pip and Herbert row quickly towards the ship. But the police are catching them.

45:07.000 --> 45:17.000
Magwitch is very angry. He hates Comppison. He jumps in the other boat and fights Comppison.

45:17.000 --> 45:22.000
They fall in the water.

45:22.000 --> 45:35.000
The big ship passes over them. Are they dead? Pip dives in the sea to rescue Magwitch.

45:35.000 --> 45:42.000
We arrest you, Abel Magwitch. But where is Comppison? He's dead.

45:42.000 --> 45:48.000
The wheels of the ship are very powerful. His body is in the water.

45:48.000 --> 45:55.000
Come with us. We are going back to London. We are going to prison. This man must die.

45:55.000 --> 46:02.000
No. He is like my father. Please don't take him.

46:07.000 --> 46:15.000
Transportation to Australia. This is the 18th century.

46:15.000 --> 46:26.000
The punishment for many crimes is hanging. Thieves and robbers, not only murderers, must hang.

46:26.000 --> 46:38.000
But this is a problem for the government. There are too many criminals. We need a new way of punishing them.

46:38.000 --> 46:48.000
The answer is transportation. This means sending criminals to Australia.

46:48.000 --> 46:57.000
Why is this a good idea? Because the thieves and robbers leave England.

46:57.000 --> 47:02.000
They can help to build a new country.

47:02.000 --> 47:13.000
What are the prison ships? These are old ships on the Thames. The Navy does not need them.

47:13.000 --> 47:21.000
They are horrible places. They are wet and dark and smelly.

47:21.000 --> 47:30.000
The convicts stay here for several months. Then they go to Australia.

47:30.000 --> 47:39.000
Some of them are dangerous criminals. They must stay in Australia for life.

47:39.000 --> 47:54.000
Some of them commit small crimes. A servant girl steals something from a shop. She goes to Australia for seven years.

47:54.000 --> 47:59.000
How do the prisoners travel to Australia?

47:59.000 --> 48:08.000
It is 15,000 miles to Australia. The journey takes a hundred days.

48:08.000 --> 48:25.000
Ships take the prisoners. Between 1787 and 1868, 162,000 male and female prisoners go from Britain to Australia.

48:25.000 --> 48:38.000
The ships are not good places. A lot of prisoners die from diseases. They have no fresh air below decks.

48:38.000 --> 48:46.000
The punishments for prisoners who make trouble are very hard.

48:46.000 --> 48:58.000
What happens in Australia? In Australia the prisoners work. They help to build new towns.

48:58.000 --> 49:11.000
Sometimes they become free men and women after a few years. Often they become important, well known and respectable people.

49:11.000 --> 49:21.000
The first farmers, brewers, millers etc. in Australia are convicts.

49:21.000 --> 49:33.000
In 1805 Solomon Wiseman is a prisoner. In 1833 he is governor of Sydney.

49:33.000 --> 49:46.000
But the serious criminals must not return to England. If they do and the police catch them, the punishment is death.

49:46.000 --> 49:55.000
Do the Victorians hang murderers? Yes. Public hangings are very popular.

49:55.000 --> 50:06.000
In the story Pip lives near Newgate prison. They hang people there. Large crowds watch.

50:06.000 --> 50:15.000
Some people pay ten pounds. A lot of money in Victorian England for a good seat.

50:15.000 --> 50:32.000
Dickens himself attends one hanging in London. He hates it. He says that he lives in a city of devils.

50:32.000 --> 50:43.000
Part 9. Joe to the rescue. The police take Pip and Magwitch back to London.

50:43.000 --> 50:51.000
I am very cold. The river is very cold. My head is bleeding.

50:51.000 --> 51:01.000
Let me hold you in my arms. Magwitch is our prisoner. He must wear chains.

51:01.000 --> 51:10.000
Now there is a big problem. The police say. We must hang Magwitch. He is a criminal.

51:10.000 --> 51:19.000
But Magwitch is very ill. He is dying. Pip is visiting him in prison.

51:19.000 --> 51:27.000
Abel, I have no father. So you are my father now. I love you.

51:27.000 --> 51:36.000
Dear boy, I love you. You are my fine gentleman. Are you happy?

51:36.000 --> 51:47.000
No. I cannot be happy. I love a beautiful woman. Her name is Estella. But she is the wife of another man.

51:47.000 --> 51:57.000
I hope you are happy soon, Pip. Goodbye. I don't have a long time to live.

51:57.000 --> 52:13.000
Abel Magwitch dies. Pip is very sad. He has no money. He has no friends in London because Herbert is working in another country.

52:13.000 --> 52:22.000
Pip owes money to the shopkeepers. They are very angry with him and take him to a house.

52:22.000 --> 52:35.000
If he wants to be free, he must pay the money. Pip is very ill. He is dreaming about his childhood.

52:35.000 --> 52:46.000
He is dreaming about Joe, his best friend. Then he wakes up. Joe is there.

52:46.000 --> 52:59.000
Come home with me, Pip. I have enough money to pay the shopkeepers. You are free. But you are poor Joe. Money is not important.

52:59.000 --> 53:05.000
You are important because Biddy and I love you.

53:05.000 --> 53:20.000
Pip goes back to the country. He lives at the forge again. He is getting better and he is beginning to think about love. He thinks...

53:20.000 --> 53:31.000
I love Estella. But she is cruel and she has no heart. Biddy is a very good person. She loves me.

53:31.000 --> 53:40.000
Pip wants to ask Biddy to marry him. But there is something he does not know.

53:40.000 --> 53:50.000
Biddy, I want to... Pip, I have some wonderful news. Joe and I are getting married today.

53:50.000 --> 54:08.000
But, well, that is wonderful news. You are my best friends. I am very happy. Let me kiss you both.

54:08.000 --> 54:27.000
Part 10, Estella. So Pip begins to think about Estella again. There is news from London. Bentley Drummel is a very bad husband. He hits Estella.

54:27.000 --> 54:34.000
She never goes out. People say that she is very unhappy.

54:34.000 --> 54:44.000
Poor Estella. She is learning to have a heart. You are a very sad Pip. Can we help you?

54:44.000 --> 54:58.000
No, my friends. I must leave England. I want to go to Africa or Australia. I want to work hard and forget my problems.

54:58.000 --> 55:07.000
Pip leaves England. He works hard in the East and tries to forget everything in the past.

55:07.000 --> 55:21.000
After 11 years, he comes back. He visits Joe and Biddy and their child. Their son's name is Little Pip.

55:21.000 --> 55:29.000
Pip decides to visit Satis House for the last time. Miss Havisham is dead.

55:29.000 --> 55:38.000
The house is not there. Only ruins. He walks in the garden.

55:38.000 --> 55:50.000
Here is the garden. I remember when I was a boy here. Estella was a beautiful little girl. And I was a poor boy from the blacksmiths family.

55:50.000 --> 56:02.000
I remember the house. I remember the clocks. But wait. There is someone in the garden. I can see a woman.

56:02.000 --> 56:08.000
She is coming towards me through the mist. Who is it?

56:09.000 --> 56:20.000
Estella comes out of the mist and meets Pip in the garden. She is still very beautiful. But her face is sad.

56:20.000 --> 56:24.000
Estella, why are you here?

56:24.000 --> 56:35.000
Bentley Dremel is dead. There was an accident with his horse. I am here to say goodbye to Satis House.

56:36.000 --> 56:39.000
And do you have a heart now?

56:39.000 --> 56:46.000
Yes, Pip. I have a heart. But it is too late.

56:46.000 --> 57:00.000
Pip is very happy to see Estella again. They talk for a long time in the garden. They hold hands. They are not young and free.

57:00.000 --> 57:06.000
They have a lot of problems. But they go out of the garden together.

57:06.000 --> 57:09.000
We are friends, Estella.

57:09.000 --> 57:13.000
We must be friends apart, Pip.

57:13.000 --> 57:24.000
Pip knows the meaning of his life. Money is not important. Being a gentleman is not important.

57:24.000 --> 57:29.000
Great expectations are not important.

57:29.000 --> 57:33.000
Friendship is important.

57:33.000 --> 57:43.000
He is friends with Estella. They are together. There is no shadow of goodbye.

